  "prompt": "Can I keep savings account if my status changes to NRI? What happens to my PPF and NPS accounts?",
  "response": "If your status changes to NRI (Non-Resident Indian), there are specific rules and regulations that apply to your savings, PPF (Public Provident Fund), and NPS (National Pension System) accounts. Here\u2019s a detailed breakdown:\n\n### Savings Account\n\n1. **Eligibility**: As an NRI, you cannot maintain a regular savings account in India. You are required to convert your existing savings account to an NRO (Non-Resident Ordinary) or NRE (Non-Resident External) account.\n   \n2. **NRO Account**: This account is suitable if you have income sources in India. It allows you to manage your Indian Rupee earnings and repatriate up to a certain limit.\n\n3. **NRE Account**: This account is suitable if you want to hold your foreign earnings in Indian Rupees. The funds in this account are fully repatriable.\n\n4. **Process**: You need to inform your bank about your change in status, and they will guide you through the conversion process. Typically, you will need to submit documents such as a copy of your passport, visa, and a letter stating your new residential status.\n\n### Public Provident Fund (PPF)\n\n1. **Existing Accounts**: If you already have a PPF account, you can continue to hold it until maturity, which is 15 years from the date of opening. You can extend it in blocks of 5 years indefinitely.\n\n2. **Contributions**: As an NRI, you cannot open a new PPF account, but you can continue to make contributions to your existing account. However, ensure you comply with the Foreign Exchange Management Act (FEMA) regulations.\n\n3. **Interest and Tax**: The interest earned on PPF remains tax-free, and the account continues to be governed by the same rules as for residents.\n\n### National Pension System (NPS)\n\n1. **Existing Accounts**: You can continue to maintain your existing NPS account even after becoming an NRI.\n\n2. **Contributions**: You can continue to contribute to your NPS account. There\u2019s no restriction on NRIs contributing to NPS, but you need to ensure that the funds are remitted from an NRE/NRO account.\n\n3. **Withdrawal**: The withdrawal rules remain the same for NRIs as for residents. You can withdraw at the age of 60, with partial withdrawals allowed under certain conditions.\n\n4. **Tax Benefits**: The tax benefits on contributions and the tax treatment of the maturity amount remain the same for NRIs as for resident Indians.\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Savings Account**: Convert to NRO/NRE account.\n- **PPF**: Continue existing account until maturity, no new accounts allowed.\n- **NPS**: Continue existing account, no restrictions on contributions, same withdrawal and tax rules apply.\n\nAlways consult with your bank and financial advisor to ensure compliance with all regulations and to understand any specific requirements or changes that may apply to your situation.",
